tanding of how the United States came to occupy the pinnacle of world power. Yet the consequences of indirect rule he documents—including anti-Americanism—reveal its shortcomings. As US efforts at democracy promotion and other forms of intervention abroad face declining support at home, Indirect Rule compels us to consider whether this method of rule ultimately advances US interests.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDependencyxHistory. 0aPower (Social sciences)xHistory. 0aWorld politics. 4aInternational Studies. 4aU.S. HISTORY. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / Diplomacy.2bisacsh  ademocracy promotion, U.S. domination, imperialism, foreign policy, Caribbean Basin, postwar Western Europe, Arab Middle East, diplomatic history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311075184040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501773754?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501773754423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501773754/original  a978-3-11-075184-0  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles